# SPA Clean URL Routing

Use this rule whenever implementing **clean/pretty URLs** in a single-page application using the **History API** (`pushState` / `popstate`) with a **server-side fallback**.

**Other names for this pattern:**
- SPA routing with clean URLs
- History API routing
- Route fallback pattern
- Pretty URL routing

---

## How It Works

```
Browser requests /products/shoes
    ↓
Server has no file at that path
    ↓
Server fallback → serves index.html (the shell)
    ↓
JS reads window.location.pathname → "/products/shoes"
    ↓
Router shows the matching in-page section/component
```

No full page reloads. No hash (#) in URLs. Browser history works normally.

---

## Server Fallback (pick your stack)

The server must serve the HTML shell for any path that isn't a static asset or API route.

### Node.js / Express
```js
// Order matters — always follow this sequence:

// 1. Static assets
app.use(express.static('public'));

// 2. API routes
app.use('/api', apiRouter);

// 3. SPA fallback — catches everything else
app.get('*', (req, res) => {
  res.sendFile(path.resolve('public', 'index.html'));
});
```

> **Multi-shell variant** — if each section has its own HTML file:
> ```js
> app.get('/dashboard/*', (req, res) => res.sendFile(...'dashboard.html'));
> app.get('/settings/*',  (req, res) => res.sendFile(...'settings.html'));
> // keep API routes above these
> ```

### Nginx
```nginx
location / {
  try_files $uri $uri/ /index.html;
}
```

### Apache .htaccess
```apache
RewriteEngine On
RewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-f
RewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-d
RewriteRule ^ /index.html [L]
```

### Vite / Webpack Dev Server
```js
// vite.config.js
export default { server: { historyApiFallback: true } }

// webpack.config.js
devServer: { historyApiFallback: true }
```

